Conversational programs to facilitate communication between computers and humans using natural language have existed for many years \cite{Thompson2007,SHAH2016}. 
However, those were very limited systems in terms of the capacity of the models used at the time \cite{Hutchens1996}. 

In recent years, several authors have carried out studies on the convenience of integrating chatbots in teaching, evaluating their characteristics. 
Thus, Coniam \cite{Coniam2014} evaluates several systems, concluding that they are still in an early stage to be used with guarantees.
Likewise, Tallyn et al. \cite{Tallyn2018} evaluates a system related to a very specific topic that is suitable for answering specific questions using a chat.
Finally, Smutny et al. \cite{Smutny2020} present a review study examining the educational chatbots in Facebook Messenger with focus to identify characteristics such as language, subject matter and platform.

According to \cite{Roblyer2010}, using either tools such as mobile devices or teaching strategies based on gamification \cite{Yildirim2017} can improve student motivation.
In this sense, Pimmer et al. \cite{Pimmer2019} carried out a series of experiments with technological tools whose results showed positive perception and acceptance of the use of technology in teaching and learning, since students are used to using those media with which they can express themselves freely. 




